text:
2/2

Industry supporters contend that Republican lawmakers will hesitate to go along with Trump’s attempt to liquidate IRA, noting the tax credits have spurred investment and created jobs in their districts.

Michael Catanzaro, a former White House special assistant to Trump and president of Republican lobbying shop CGCN Group, disputes that notion.

“Let me address a canard that is often spoken here in Washington, which is that a lot of the investment under IRA is being done in red states and red districts,” he told a recent webinar held by law firm Norton Rose Fulbright.
He argued that while there are a lot of announced projects around the country, which is great, “An announced project is not a built project.”

Part of the reason there are only announced projects in many places is the “permitting process is such a disaster,” he said, blaming permitting delays on a plethora of new rules, regulations and other guidance issued by the Biden administration.
“Just because you have projects being announced in red states does not mean that Republicans will have a hard time repealing large parts of the IRA,” he added.

John Gimigliano, principal-in-charge of federal legislative and regulatory services for KPMG in Washington, noted on the webinar that Trump and Republicans want to extend 2017 federal tax cuts for businesses and individuals that were enacted in his term and expire next year.

He agrees it is a "false hope to assume that the number of potential investments in Republican states will act as a firewall against repeal."

Gimigliano added: "There may be some reluctance, but remember that you are forcing Republicans to decide between raising taxes on millions of individuals, including middle-income folks, and repealing incentives for a handful of energy projects in their states or districts."

The US Congressional Joint Committee on Taxation, which is comprised of five lawmakers from the Senate Finance Committee and five from the House Ways and Means Committee, estimates extending the 2017 tax cuts will cost $4.3trn.
Trump sees axing IRA tax breaks and other spending as helping pay the cost of a tax cut extension.

Still, enough Republican lawmakers favour IRA tax credits for carbon capture and hydrogen development, critical minerals mining and processing, and re-shoring of manufacturing especially from China.

This makes it unlikely these and other incentives will be scrapped by Congress.

text:
Artificial intelligence (AI) has long been intertwined with futuristic visions and technological advancement, but in 2024, its assimilation into the political domain has become a formidable reality. With the presidential election underway, the issue at hand is not AI's potential— which is enormous—but its governance. The oversight by the Federal Election Commission to refrain from enacting new regulations on AI usage in this critical democratic process carries profound implications.

Let us pivot our focus to the unsettling incidents of disinformation already surfacing: a computer-generated image of Taylor Swift endorsing former President Donald Trump stirred up controversy, necessitating a clarification from the pop icon herself. Furthermore, a fabricated video of Vice President Kamala Harris' voice disseminated by entrepreneur Elon Musk adds layers of complexity to political discourse. By extending beyond mere digital trickery, these instances violate public trust and the essence of free and fair elections.

The modus operandi of external forces, like Russia and Iran, has been to weaponize AI against the electoral process. OpenAI's discovery of these antagonistic efforts reaffirms the need for vigilance. It is not hyperbole to state that the future of democracy could hinge on our ability to effectively audit and regulate the use of AI.

We must delve into discussions of how AI will continue to shape not only this election but many to come. It is imperative to unravel the tapestry of legal, ethical, and social threads that will define our societal landscape. Revisiting the founding fathers' intention of a government "by the people, for the people," one questions—can we keep this ethos intact amidst the digital renaissance, or will we witness its unraveling at the hands of unregulated AI?

As constituents and consumers of media, our responsibility is heightened. Supporting platforms like NPR's 1A not only fosters informed conversations but also sustains a sphere where questions, facts, and enlightenment reign over AI-generated confusion. Engagement and education become the bulwarks against manipulative AI practices. We are encouraged to connect, inquire, and even lend our voices by contributing to public radio stations or subscribing ad-free to further this mission.

The crux of this discourse is not to stifle innovation but to ensure technology serves democracy's loftiest goals. As we stride into the digital age's political arena, let us be guided by a compass that points steadfastly towards integrity and transparency. This election shall serve as a crucible, testing our collective will to maintain the democratic sanctity in the face of AI's seductive power. Can we keep it? This question beckons a deeper reflection not merely on policy but on our enduring commitment to liberty and truth.

author/description: Truth, Justice and American Values. These are times that try our souls 🦅🇺🇸
text: The claim by Donald Trump regarding schools turning children transgender without parental consent is not only devoid of factual basis but also dangerously misleading. There's no widespread policy or legal framework in the U.S. allowing schools to perform or initiate transgender "operations" or any gender-affirming treatments on minors without parental consent. Such treatments, especially surgeries, are not casually decided upon or performed on minors; they require extensive psychological evaluation, consent from parents, and in many cases, court approval due to the complexity and ethical considerations involved. Trump's assertion plays into fears by implying a loss of parental rights, which ignores the legal and ethical standards in place. Moreover, it contributes to a climate of fear and misinformation around transgender healthcare, which is typically approached with caution, involving therapy, and often, reversible treatments like puberty blockers before any permanent changes are considered. This narrative not only misrepresents the reality of transgender healthcare practices but also undermines the rights and well-being of transgender youth, suggesting a level of intervention by schools that simply does not exist in policy or practice.
